<text>Brownian Motion

        
      

Brownian motion is a classical example in the history of modern science. The studies of Brownian motion provided indirectly a strong evidence that atoms exist. At the time when Brown discovered this motion, the theory of atom was not yet accepted. The atom theory gave a convincing explanation of Brownian motion: Particles are constantly and randomly collided by smaller particles around them; If they receive more hits from one side than the other, there will be a net force causing them to move.

In the above model, the white big particle is 100 times heavier than the smaller ones. The simulation shows that the motion of the big particle is affected by the small surrounding ones.

For a review of contemporary research on Brownian motion, see http://www.doc.ic.ac.uk/~nd/surprise_95/journal/vol4/ykl/report.html</text>
