    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;In 1827, botanist Robert Brown observed under microscope 
    that pollen grains suspended in fluid move in a zigzag path. In 1889 G.L. 
    Gouy found that the &amp;quot;Brownian&amp;quot; movement was more rapid for smaller 
    particles. In 1900 F.M. Exner carried out the first quantitative studies, 
    measuring how the motion depended on temperature and particle size. In 
    1905, Albert Einstein proposed the first mathematical theory of Brownian 
    motion. With this model, you can easily find the relationships between the 
    motion of the suspension particle and its mass and the system&apos;s 
    temperature by yourself, and see what used to be only seen by a genius 
    more than 100 years ago.&lt;/font&gt;
